-Difference Between VM Arguments and Application Arguments
-1. Application Arguments (args[] in main)
- These are arguments passed to the main method of your Java application.
- They are accessed via String[] args in public static void main(String[] args).
- They are specific to the application logic and can be used for input parameters, file paths, user options, etc.
- Passed after the JAR file in the command line.
-­¤ö╣ Example (Passing application arguments):
-sh
-CopyEdit
-java -jar my-app.jar arg1 arg2 arg3
-­¤ö╣ How to Access in Code:
-java
-CopyEdit
-public class MainClass {
-    public static void main(String[] args) {
-        System.out.println("Application Arguments:");
-        for (String arg : args) {
-            System.out.println(arg);
-        }
-    }
-}
-
-2. VM Arguments (JVM Options)
- These configure the JVM itself (memory settings, garbage collection, system properties, etc.).
- They are not passed to main(String[] args).
- Used for setting heap size, garbage collector, system properties, etc.
- Passed before the -jar option.
-­¤ö╣ Example (Passing VM arguments):
-sh
-CopyEdit
-java -Xmx512m -Denv=prod -jar my-app.jar arg1 arg2
- -Xmx512m --> Sets max heap memory to 512MB.
- -Denv=prod --> Defines a system property (System.getProperty("env")).
- arg1 arg2 are application arguments.
-­¤ö╣ How to Access VM Arguments in Code:
-java
-CopyEdit
-public class MainClass {
-    public static void main(String[] args) {
-        // Accessing application arguments
-        System.out.println("Application Arguments:");
-        for (String arg : args) {
-            System.out.println(arg);
-        }
-
-        // Accessing VM arguments (System Properties)
-        String env = System.getProperty("env", "default");
-        System.out.println("VM Argument: env = " + env);
-    }
-}
-
