-b. Security Updates
- Elytron Security Manager: WildFly 8.x introduces Elytron as the security subsystem, replacing the legacy PicketBox. You may need to refactor security realms, LDAP authentication, and role mappings.
- Keycloak Integration: If your application relies on authentication, consider Keycloak for SSO and token-based authentication.
-c. Classloading and Module Changes
- JBoss 8.x might introduce new classloading mechanisms. If your application depends on external JARs, verify module dependencies and ensure that MANIFEST.MF and jboss-deployment-structure.xml are configured correctly.
-d. JDBC and DataSource Changes
- Verify the compatibility of JDBC drivers and update datasources configurations if required.
- Test database connection pools and JNDI naming consistency.
-e. Messaging (If Applicable)
- HornetQ to ActiveMQ Artemis Migration: If your application uses JMS, JBoss 8.x may have replaced HornetQ with ActiveMQ Artemis. Update configurations accordingly.
-f. Other Possible Issues
- Updated transaction handling mechanisms.
- Changes in thread pool management.
- Modifications in deployment descriptors (web.xml, ejb-jar.xml, application.xml).
-
-2. Java 8 to Java 11 Migration
-Moving from Java 8 to Java 11 is a significant upgrade since Java 11 is a Long-Term Support (LTS) release and removes several deprecated APIs.
-a. Removed Java EE Modules
-Java 11 removes several EE modules that were available in Java 8:
- javax.xml.bind (JAXB)
- javax.activation
- javax.annotation
- java.corba
- java.transaction (JTA)
-­¤æē Solution: If your application depends on these, you must explicitly include dependencies via Maven or Gradle.
-b. Deprecated & Removed APIs
-Some key changes include:
- java.security.acl and SecurityManager restrictions.
- JavaFX removed (if used, it must be added as an external dependency).
- Thread.stop() completely deprecated (use alternatives like CompletableFuture).
- Process API enhancements (consider ProcessHandle and ProcessBuilder).
-c. Reflection & Internal APIs
- Java 11 enforces strong encapsulation of internal APIs (e.g., sun.misc.Unsafe is now restricted).
- If your code relies on setAccessible(true), it may require the --add-opens flag.
-d. Garbage Collection (GC) Changes
- G1GC is default in Java 11, replacing CMS.
- ZGC and Epsilon GC introduced.
- If your application fine-tunes GC behavior, review JVM options.
-e. TLS and Security Enhancements
- Java 11 defaults to TLS 1.2+ and disables weaker cipher suites.
- Some SSLSocketFactory methods may be deprecated.
-f. Runtime Arguments and Tooling
- Java 11 removes Javaws (WebStart) and the Applet API.
- Some JVM options (-XX:+UseConcMarkSweepGC, -Xverify:none) are removed.
- Ensure build tools like Maven, Gradle, and Ant are upgraded.
